  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'Ninth Day: Matching the Rhymes of Cheong-yeon''s Poem'
  author: Seok Seon-tan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A song rings out in golden-threaded robes—
    wherever chrysanthemums bloom, I return intoxicated.
    On rivers and lakes, the months drift in wine and zither's song,
    yet few are the travelers on the temple's tower stairs.

    Ten thousand ravines fill with rain, crimson leaves spread everywhere,
    while from all four peaks white clouds fly forth at dawn.
    Leaning against the rail, my eyes fill with autumn's sorrow—
    each year when leaves fall, my heart and all my plans grow distant.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'golden-threaded robes' reference evokes a classical celebration of the ninth day, a traditional festival time in East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The monastery setting grounds this meditation in the speaker's Buddhist monastic life.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet reflects the Buddhist theme of impermanence—how external time (falling leaves) never aligns with our inner intentions.
